One was seen early in the day and then towards the end of our stay.  May or may not have been the same bird; however, I think it was the same by the markings.  Had great, close looks at it, especially through the spotting scope.  It did a fair amount of vocalization, too, which was nice to have the audio confirmation to go with the visual ID.
Was a little confused by these guys at first.  They were pretty high up in the air and soaring instead of the usual heavy flapping I expect from GBHs.

A nice morning at the harbor.  After several days of east winds and warmer temperature, the wind shifted that night to out of the Northwest and skies cleared.  Light Northerly winds continued in the morning and the birds came with it.  The start of school meant there were no kids and pretty much no beach-goes showed up until about 2pm EDT.  Several birders from Canton stopped by and tipped me off to the Night-herons at the pond area of the harbor.Temperatures were in the low 70s and sky was mostly sunny.
With D Sanders and D Linzell

With Andy Jones, Michelle Leighty, and Ben Winger. Chasing the BTGU found 2 days earlier. Began at sunrise east of the bridge over the river, scanning north into the industrial rectangular impoundments within the harbor. Spent over an hour scanning the flock of 3,000 BOGU with smattering of larger species mixed in, then went west to the Museum at the River overlook, just north and west of the bridge. Around 9AM we left and went to the park east of the industrial complex for about an hour, then returned briefly to the museum after seeing Cave Swallows reported from that location on OH birds listserv.

About 25 deg F with light south wind, partly sunny.  There has been about six inches of snow and ice cover for several days.  The horned larks were in the street.  We had single digit degrees F weather last night, and the river upstream of the dam had its surface almost completely frozen.  Most waterfowl were below the dam.  The eagle had a white head, but I dont know if the head was completely white.

62 deg F, partly cloudy.  Light north wind.  A cold front came through yesterday.  I parked at the Hamilton water treatment plant, walked downstream to the opening just beyond the Fairfield water treatment plant and back, hardly leaving the bike trail.  There were young wood ducks in the old channel.  The mallards, none in bright male plumage, are congregating in the middle of the river.  There were many more (perhpas 30) swallows high over the river than I identified and counted.

29 deg F, intermittent snow cover.  I parked at Joyce Park and met Bob Lacker:  we walked to Tetanus Beach and looped back.  We met Mike Busam and drove to Hamilton water treatment plant and walked to shorebird island and the low dam.
singing male. Adult male and female with feed seen on June 17, 2012

Viewed in flooded field next to airport on N Gilmore road. Was feeding near a few male and female rusty blackbirds. It was a uniform glossy purple/black color with no rusty patches. The yellow in its eye was a lot brighter when compared to the nearby rusty blackbirds as well. Was alot smaller and had a shorter tail than a grackle.
Light snow and about one inch snow cover.

First-winter bird. Robust bird resembling a Herring Gull in size but with a great deal of white edging on the scapulars, lesser, middle and greater coverts. Pronounced slope to forhead, stout dark bill, darkest at the tip, dark iris, chocolate-gray plumage, pink legs. Bird has been seen by multiple observers in the 2-3 weeks that it has been present. Similar species - much larger than ring-billed with which it associated (size comparison photograph available). Iceland Gull is paler, whiter in plumage, white light iris and less contrasting wingtips (Kumliens) [From documentation form]. obsr44064 David A. The bird was first spotted by Larry Rosche.  Extreme excitement!  Larry literally ran to get Tom Bartlett, who came armed with camera. Photos were taken, and most of the group saw the bird.  The bird was spotted 3 separate times in the afternoon.  He posed beautifully.  Tom has provided more information on location via the Ohio-Birds list serve.

The bird was singing from a sycamore tree at the parking lot on the east side of the road just south of the nature center turnoff. This seemed like an odd place for this species. It sang repeatedly but all we saw of it was flying from one tree to another. The song is very distinctive. It was a buzzy song of several notes. One song would end on a note going up and the next on a note going down. I know this song very well, having heard it many times over the last 30 years. We went back to this location about an hour later and the bird was no longer there. The habitat didnt look good for this species and there is probably a good chance the bird moved on.	obsr99398	Doug	Overacker	S18510086	eBird - Traveling Count	EBIRD	180	3.219		3	1		1	1

Some folks on www.whatbird.com seem to think this may be a Common Tern. Thoughts? --
from silo to Inter urban to bridge to shelter to culvert and back
Flushed from wet field.  Dumpy shape, oversized bill, zig-zag flight, bleating call.

Did a preserve walk that was generally the north end of the preserve north of the visitor center.  We walked prairie, forest, ponds, and scrub and most things were where one would expect to find them.  The final species total was 65 among all participants.  I know only one person saw a hummer and we decided no one encountered a TT or a DW.  I think the other species were TS, OO, NM?, M, HS?, CGR?, AC? but I dont know and I dont remember seeing them myself.  My numbers on some things could be ultraconservative.  Im including 2 Mutes that were in the first pond by the entrance and 3 RTHs that I saw in the south end of the preserve on my way out.
I got there sometime between 830 and 9.  And this should really be an area count of most of the garden.----Dead compared to yesterday.  Quit when it started raining.
middle lot>overlook>flooded field>s. grass path>middle lot----Still no SEO.  Dogwalker had RTH mob BE Sunday morning as well as NH, CH, and TV.

south lot>s mowed path>overlook>flooded field>middle paved path>w side of bike path>south lot>dog park>Duck creek via canoe landing>s mowed path> south lot----Nothing new going on.  Possibly MD and thought maybe Banks for a bit but didnt get a second look.

Walked down to the river, upriver a little bit and back the same way.----Picked up a few more migrants but birding in general was still fairly slow like it was for most of the day.  And only one maybe-Nashville warbler though I didnt walk the bike path.
Barred rufous breast and evenly banded tail.  Probably BWH or adult CH.
A small flock of 6 birds.  Eye Whte.  Green iridescence
Flushed at Otto Armleder Memorial Park near the dog park
Flushed at Armleder.  The quietest WS ever.  Seen by 3 of us.
Briefly watched it eat another kill.  Sparrow or wren I think.
Molting.  Eventually got something bigger than a sparrow.

11:00AM between markers 15 & 16, Ben Morrison was a bit ahead of me and pointed down towards the water to the north of the boardwalk saying he heard something like a waterthrush and wanted me to hear it. As I got to the railing the bird let out its classic full song beginning with its 3 very loud, ringing, fairly low range, staccato with increasing speed introductory notes that precede the more jumbled finish to the song. I immediately said, That's a Kirtland's Warbler and Sharri Jackson who was with us and travels to Mio every year readily agreed. Ben was the only one able to pick out the singer from the underbrush 3' off the ground, 25' off the trail. The bird was pretty much a silhouette but was described as a large warbler with a long tail which it was constantly pumping. The Pacific Loon was a stake out.  Observed well in the scope.  Rich gray on back of neck and top of head; thin small bill compare to nearby Common Loon.  In profile the neat demarcation between white of throat and gray of neck is distinctive with no indentions in the the color of the neck as would be the case in Common Loons.
Made loop around the west pond.
Birded the Pine Ridge area (north and west). Sunny, winds calm, 49F.

small (about 6 inches), earless, striped owl sitting on ground under small tree/shrub (evergreen if I remember correctly) with yellow eyes open.  I saw it as I dove down the street.  I thought it was a baby owl, and I stopped and walked over to it, but it did not move.  It did not look injured, so I left it alone.  A few years later I realized it was a Saw-Whet Owl after seeing it in a bird guide I purchased.
